 to the plans of Christopher Colles, builder of the first American steam engine, and of Joseph Browne, the first to call for a mainland water source for this island-city. In this vividly written true-life fable of the "Fools of Gotham," the chief obstacle to the aqueduct is the Manhattan Company. Masterminded by Aaron Burr, with the complicity of Alexander Hamilton and other leading New Yorkers, the company was a ruse, serving as the charter for a bank--today's Chase Manhattan. The cholera epidemic of 1832 and the great fire three years later were instrumental in forcing the city's leaders to finally unite and regain New York's water rights. Koeppel's account of the developments leading up to the Croton Aqueduct reveals it as a triumph not only of inspired technology but of political will. With over forty archival photographs and drawings, Water for Gotham demonstrates the deep interconnections between natural resource management, urban planning, and civic leadership. As New York today retakes its waterfront and boasts famous tap water, this book is a valuable reminder of how much vision and fortitude are required to make a great city function and thrive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAbove Par.  aAbutment.  aAlley.  aAppraiser.  aAtlantic Ocean.  aBanana.  aBiogeography.  aBiography.  aBiologist.  aBourgeoisie.  aBrine pool.  aBusiness class.  aCaleb (Buffy the Vampire Slayer).  aCast iron pipe.  aCatskill Mountains.  aChairman.  aCharles Darwin.  aChief engineer.  aCholera.  aChristopher Colles.  aCoenties Slip.  aCoffeehouse.  aCommissioner.  aConstitutionality.  aCroton Aqueduct.  aCroton River.  aCulvert.  aCustomer.  aDeep sea.  aDesigner.  aDrinking water.  aDutch West India Company.  aEast Pacif